Dynamic evaluation improves the state-of-the-art perplexity on WikiText-2, and provides a significantly greater improvement than neural caching to both base models. This suggests that dynamic evaluation is effective at exploiting regularities that co-occur across non-shuffled documents.
7.2 CHARACTER-LEVEL LANGUAGE MODELLING
We consider dynamic evaluation on the text83, and Hutter Prize (Hutter, 2006) datasets. The Hutter Prize dataset is comprised of Wikipedia text, and includes XML and characters from non-Latin languages. It is 100 million UTF-8 bytes long and contains 205 unique bytes. Similarly to other reported results, we use a 90-5-5 split for training, validation, and testing. The text8 dataset is also
